# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-vegan-society
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] A **501(c)(3) organization** is a United States corporation, trust, unincorporated association, or other type of organization exempt from federal income tax under section 501(c)(3) of Title 26 of the United States Code.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] It is one of the 29 types of 501(c) nonprofit organizations in the U.S.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] The 501(c)(3) exemption applies also for any non-incorporated community chest, fund, cooperating association or foundation organized and operated exclusively for those purposes.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] There are also supporting organizations—often referred to in shorthand form as *Friends of* organizations.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] 26 U.S.C. § 170 provides a deduction for federal income tax purposes, for some donors who make charitable contributions to most types of 501(c)(3) organizations, among others.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Regulations specify which such deductions must be verifiable to be allowed (e.g., receipts for donations of $250 or more).
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] The basic requirement of obtaining tax-exempt status is that the organization is specifically limited in powers to purposes that the IRS classifies as tax-exempt purposes.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] This limiting of the powers is crucial to obtaining tax exempt status with the IRS and then on the state level.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Organizations acquire 501(c)(3) tax exemption by filing IRS Form 1023.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] As of 2006, the form must be accompanied by an $850 filing fee if the yearly gross receipts for the organization are expected to average $10,000 or more.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] If yearly gross receipts are expected to average less than $10,000, the filing fee is reduced to $400.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] The IRS released a software tool called Cyber Assistant in 2013, which was succeeded by Form 1023-EZ in 2014.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] There is an alternative way for an organization to obtain status if an organization has applied for a determination and either there is an actual controversy regarding a determination or the Internal Revenue Service has failed to make a determination.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Prior to December 30, 1969, nonprofit organizations could declare themselves to be tax-exempt under Section 501(c)(3) without first obtaining Internal Revenue Service recognition by filing Form 1023 and receiving a determination letter.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] A nonprofit organization that did so prior to that date could still be subject to challenge of its status by the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] An individual may not take a tax deduction on gifts made to a 501(c)(3) organization that is organized and operated exclusively for the testing for public safety.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] In the case of tuition fees paid to a private 501(c)(3) school or a church school, the payments are not tax-deductible charitable contributions because they are payments for services rendered to the payee or the payee's children.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] The payments are not tax-deductible charitable contributions even if a significant portion of a church school's curriculum is religious education.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] For a payment to be a tax-deductible charitable contribution, it must be a voluntary transfer of money or other property with no expectation of procuring financial benefit equal to the transfer amount.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Before donating to a 501(c)(3) organization, a donor can consult the searchable online IRS list of charitable organizations to verify that the organization qualifies to receive tax-deductible charitable contributions.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Consumers may file IRS Form 13909, with documentation, to complain about inappropriate or fraudulent (i.e., fundraising, political campaigning, lobbying) activities by any 501(c)(3) organization.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Most 501(c)(3) must disclose the names and addresses of certain large donors to the Internal Revenue Service on their annual returns, but this information is not required to be made available to the public, unless the organization is an independent foundation.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Churches are generally exempt from this reporting requirement.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Every 501(c)(3) organization must make available for public inspection its application for tax-exemption, including its Form 1023 or Form 1023-EZ and any attachments, supporting documents, and follow-up correspondence with the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Annual returns must be publicly available for a three-year period beginning with the due date of the return, including any extension of time for filing.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] The Internal Revenue Service provides information about specific 501(c)(3) organizations through its Tax Exempt Organization Search online.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] A private nonprofit organization, GuideStar, provides information on 501(c)(3) organizations.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] ProPublica's Nonprofit Explorer provides copies of each organization's Form 990 and, for some organizations, audited financial statements.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] WikiCharities, is a nonprofit database of nonprofits and charities by name, location, and topic, that allows each organization to report its financials, leadership, contacts, and other activities.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] However, Open990 was a searchable database of information about organizations that had to shut down due to IRS delays in posting information online.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations are prohibited from supporting political candidates, as a result of the Johnson Amendment enacted in 1954.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations are subject to limits on lobbying, having a choice between two sets of rules establishing an upper bound for their lobbying activities.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations risk loss of their tax-exempt status if these rules are violated.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] An organization that loses its 501(c)(3) status due to being engaged in political activities cannot subsequently qualify for 501(c)(3) status.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] As a result, it is common for 501(c)(3) organizations to have affiliated nonprofits that are classified as 501(c)(4) organizations, allowing the affiliate to engage in political activity without threatening 501(c)(3) status.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Churches must meet specific requirements to obtain and maintain tax-exempt status; these are outlined in "IRS Publication 1828: Tax Guide for Churches and Religious Organizations".
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] This guide outlines activities allowed and not allowed by churches under the 501(c)(3) designation.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Schools for the preparation of its ministers.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Having an established congregation served by an organized ministry is of central importance.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Points 4, 6, 8, 11, 12, and 13 are also especially important.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Nevertheless, the 14-point list is a guideline; it is not intended to be all-encompassing, and other facts and circumstances may be relevant factors.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Although there is no definitive definition of a church for Internal Revenue Code purposes, in 1986 the United States Tax Court said that "A church is a coherent group of individuals and families that join together to accomplish the religious purposes of mutually held beliefs.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] The United States Tax Court has stated that, while a church can certainly broadcast its religious services by radio, radio broadcasts themselves do not constitute a congregation unless there is a group of people physically attending those religious services.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] A church can conduct worship services in various specific locations rather than in one official location.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] A church may have a significant number of people associate themselves with the church on a regular basis, even if the church does not have a traditional established list of individual members.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] In order to qualify as a tax-exempt church, church activities must be a significant part of the organization's operations.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] An organization whose operations include a substantial nonexempt commercial purposes, such as operating restaurants and grocery stores in a manner consistent with a particular religion's religious beliefs does not qualify as a tax-exempt church.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] In practice, hospital policies often don't cover outside contracted physicians or narrowly defined medically necessary services, leaving patients who technically qualify for charity care still responsible for significant medical bills.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Organizations described in section 501(c)(3) are prohibited from conducting political campaign activities to intervene in elections to public office.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Since section 501(c)(3)'s political-activity prohibition was enacted, "commentators and litigants have challenged the provision on numerous constitutional grounds", such as freedom of speech, vagueness, and equal protection and selective prosecution.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Historically, Supreme Court decisions, such as *Regan v.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Taxation with Representation of Washington*, suggested that the Court, if it were to squarely examine the political-activity prohibition of § 501(c)(3), would uphold it against a constitutional challenge.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] However, some have suggested that a successful challenge to the political activities prohibition of Section 501(c)(3) might be more plausible in light of *Citizens United v.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] In contrast to the prohibition on political campaign interventions by all section 501(c)(3) organizations, public charities (but not private foundations) may conduct a limited amount of lobbying to influence legislation.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Although the law states that "no substantial part" of a public charity's activities can go to lobbying, charities with large budgets may lawfully expend a million dollars (under the "expenditure" test) or more (under the "substantial part" test) per year on lobbying.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] The Internal Revenue Service has never defined the term "substantial part" with respect to lobbying.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] To establish a safe harbor for the "substantial part" test, the United States Congress enacted §501(h), called the Conable election after its author, Representative Barber Conable.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] The section establishes limits based on operating budget that a charity can use to determine if it meets the substantial test.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] This changes the prohibition against direct intervention in partisan contests only for lobbying.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] The organization is now presumed in compliance with the substantiality test if they work within the limits.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] The Conable election requires a charity to file a declaration with the IRS and file a functional distribution of funds spreadsheet with their Form 990.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] IRS form 5768 is required to make the Conable election.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to conduct some or all of its charitable activities outside the United States.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to award grants to foreign charitable organizations if the grants are intended for charitable purposes and the grant funds are subject to the 501(c)(3) organization's control.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Additional procedures are required of 501(c)(3) organizations that are private foundations.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] Donors' contributions to a 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible only if the contribution is for the use of the 501(c)(3) organization, and that the 501(c)(3) organization is not merely serving as an agent or conduit of a foreign charitable organization.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] The 501(c)(3) organization's management should review the grant application from the foreign organization, decide whether to award the grant based on the intended use of the funds, and require continuous oversight based on the use of funds.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] If the donor imposes a restriction or earmark that the contribution must be used for foreign activities, then the contribution is deemed to be for the foreign organization rather than the 501(c)(3) organization, and the contribution is not tax-deductible.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] The purpose of the grant to the foreign organization cannot include endorsing or opposing political candidates for elected office in any country.
[src:american-vegan-society/501-c-3-organization] If a 501(c)(3) organization sets up and controls a foreign subsidiary to facilitate charitable work in a foreign country, then donors' contributions to the 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible even if intended to fund the foreign charitable activities.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:american-vegan-society/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] The film opens with footage of a NASA rocket launch, an animation of the Solar System, and a quote from Deuteronomy 30:19 about choosing between life and death (illustrated with images of Earth as seen from space, contrasted with an exploding atom bomb).
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] This is followed by a statement that humanity has not been caring for the planet properly according to Jewish teachings, which precedes a section about ancient Jewish texts and sacred words that provide "specific instructions on how to be custodians of the world in which we live".
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] Throughout the film, quotes from the Torah are contrasted with the various environmental threats facing humanity today; the quotes are also illustrated with close-ups of Hebrew scrolls, Jews praying, and scenes of nature.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] The Earth is again seen from space and the camera moves in to focus on Israel, which the narrator cites as a microcosm of current global problems related to air and water pollution, overpopulation, climate change, and health concerns.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] The film moves on to look at global problems, with scenes shot all over the world.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] The focus then shifts to the United States, where all the relevant issues are discussed in detail.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] Reference is made to *Livestock's Long Shadow*, a 2006 report by the Food and Agriculture Organization which claimed that livestock agriculture produces more greenhouse gases than all of the world's vehicles combined.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] Next comes a brief presentation, illustrated with simple animated charts, on how meat production is an inefficient way to produce food for a hungry world.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] This moves into footage of animal abuse on feedlots and in factory farms, and the pollution produced by these facilities.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] The film then focuses on the advantages of vegetarianism for reducing pollution and solving world hunger.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] With a change of diet toward vegetarianism, the film asserts that many of these environmental and health problems can be solved.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] After some fast-moving images of people and nature accompanied by music, the film ends with the same statement from Deuteronomy about "life and death" being narrated over a shot of a sunrise.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] The idea for the film was inspired by the writings of Richard H.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz (*Judaism and Vegetarianism*, *Judaism and Global Survival*, etc.) who also served as associate producer.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz had seen the Christian Vegetarian Association's 2006 film, *Honoring God's Creation*, and felt that a similar film would be effective in the Jewish community.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] At the time, he envisioned the film to be about 30 minutes long, though the final film ended up being 60 minutes long.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] Production began in 2005 with a basic proposal and outline in the JVNA's newsletter, along with a statement that Lionel Friedberg was willing to make the film for "a very low fee, basically to cover his costs".
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] The film was funded by the JVNA through private contributions.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] Preliminary drafts of the script were circulated among members of the JVNA advisory committee and others for input, after which the script went through numerous revisions.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] Meanwhile, Schwartz and Friedberg set about interviewing possible participants and filming footage of nature in both Israel and the United States.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] The showing of slaughterhouse footage was controversial, with some members of a test audience in Staten Island seeing it as propaganda.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] Friedberg recalled, "Richard and I were accused of making a propaganda film for the vegetarian movement.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] We were accused of showing 'horrors that are impossible to watch'." However, he maintained that the graphic footage was necessary.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] In October and November 2007, *A Sacred Duty* was released direct-to-video and on DVD, with public showings in both Israel and the United States.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] Over 35,000 copies were distributed free of charge to synagogues, educational institutions, and individuals, complete with permission to show the film without having to pay the filmmakers any royalties.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] In addition, permission was granted to the public to duplicate and distribute the film free of charge.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-sacred-duty] Numerous short excerpts from the film were edited and re-posted by various YouTube users, and the full version became available on YouTube in January 2008.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] It is a foundational essay advocating for vegetarianism, maintaining that a plant-based diet is essential for bodily health, moral virtue, and social justice.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that meat consumption is unnatural, a "slow but certain poison", causing disease, which "pollutes" the body, and leads to vice and depravity.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He prescribes the return to a "natural" vegetable diet.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] This work is regarded as one of the earliest and most fervent defenses of vegetarianism in English literature.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley wrote four essays on the subject of vegetarianism, "A Vindication of Natural Diet" (1813), the note in *Queen Mab*, in a section of "A Refutation of Deism" (1814), and "On the Vegetable System of Diet", which was published posthumously in 1929.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley first experimented with a vegetarian diet while at the University of Oxford according to Thomas Jefferson Hogg.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley began a vegetarian diet on 1 March 1812 along with his first wife Harriet Westbrook.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley began composing the essay in October–November 1812.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley met John Frank Newton during 1812-1813 and influenced his views on vegetarianism.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Historian Keith Thomas has noted that Newton's *Return to Nature* "provided much of the basis" for Shelley's *A Vindication of Natural Diet*.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The work has been republished since 1813, beginning with an abridged version which was published in Boston by March, Capen, and Lyon in an American collection *Vegetable Diet: As Sanctioned by Medical Men, and by Experience in All Ages*, edited by William A.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The essay was reprinted in 1884 in a new edition in London by Frederick Pitman and by John Heywood and the Vegetarian Society in Manchester.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The original title page was reproduced: *A Vindication of Natural Diet.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Being One in a Series of Notes to Queen Mab (A Philosophical Poem).* London: Printed for J.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The new edition featured a preface by Henry Stephens Salt and William Axon.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In 1904, the work was republished in London by C.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Daniel as *A Vindication of Natural Diet and Extracts from the Works of Dr.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley used the imagery of slaughtering a lamb.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In the novel *Frankenstein; or, The Modern Prometheus* (1818), which he is acknowledged to have contributed to, the Being is portrayed as a vegetarian.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The Being explained his vegetarian diet to Victor Frankenstein: "My food is not that of man.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] I do not destroy the lamb and the kid to glut my appetite; acorns and berries afford me sufficient nourishment." Shelley's views on vegetarianism are routinely incorrectly attributed to his wife.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In *Laon and Cythna*, republished as *The Revolt of Islam* (1817), Fifth Canto, the Festival of nations held after the Revolution is a banquet where no meat is served.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The feast is vegetarian: "Never again may blood of bird or beast/ Stain with its venomous stream a human feast".
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] This is "The banquet of the free" where the guests are described as "reclining as they ate, of Liberty,/ And Hope, and Justice".
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The festival was not polluted by gore, "But piled on high, an overflowing store/ Of pomegranates, and citrons, fairest fruit,/ Melons, and dates, and figs, and many a root".
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that eating meat was unnatural.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He maintained that diseases and immorality arose from mankind's "unnatural habits of life".
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] A meatless diet was the best regimen for maintaining a healthy and disease-free lifestyle.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He wrote that human diseases could be decreased by a return to a natural vegetable diet.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that eating meat was a practice that polluted the body with syphilis and resulted in other ailments.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In *A Vindication of Natural Diet* he wrote, "Should ever a physician be born with the genius of Locke, I am persuaded that he might trace all bodily and mental derangements to our unnatural habits," these unnatural habits being the consumption of meat.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He cited the allegory of Prometheus who stole fire from the gods which enabled mankind to cook meat, thereby screening the disgust and horror of dead flesh.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He concluded that a person with compassion and empathy for animals, "rising from a meal of roots", would be able to maintain a healthy and balanced diet and lifestyle.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley presented examples of how a vegetarian diet resulted in longevity and an increased lifespan.
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The only threat of death will be that of natural, old age, that "old age would be our last and our only malady".
[src:american-vegan-society/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The two rules he prescribes for a natural diet are to never eat anything that was alive and to drink only distilled water.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] The **American Vegan Society** (**AVS**) is a New Jersey–based nonprofit organization that promotes veganism in the United States.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] The organization publishes *American Vegan* quarterly magazine, which is sent to members of the society (earlier issues are published on the website), and books about veganism (since 1964).
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] The organization educates about a vegan diet.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] It sponsors Dynamic Harmlessness Day annually on November 2, the birthday of the late H.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] Jay Dinshah, cofounder of the American Vegan Society.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] It has two YouTube channels, "Powerful Vegan Messages" and "American Vegan Society".
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] It administers the AVS Speakers Bureau (18 popular vegan speakers from throughout the United States) and vegan conferences (the first annual event was held in 1960; bylaws require an annual vegan conference).
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] The AVS administers cooking classes, gourmet vegan dinners by culinary students, encouraging culinary students to learn vegan cooking by hosting events with only vegan food, and other food events.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] Currently this is four AVS-coordinated and hosted events each year; the template for these events is used increasingly throughout America.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] Outreach at public events (vegan books, vegan literature, and speaking about veganism).
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] Other support for direct inquiries, consulting for vegan community outreach.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] It collects, aggregates, and publishes a comprehensive list of vegan-oriented VegFests around the United States.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] Prior to broad and widely-accessible search capabilities of the Internet, the American Vegan Society published networking and business resources which supported vegan lifestyle.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] Jay Dinshah founded the American Vegan Society.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] Later that year Dinshah married the English-born Freya Smith.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] Freya, whose parents were active in The Vegan Society (of England), contributed to the early growth of the American Vegan Society and is president of the AVS today.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] The American Vegan Society is headquartered at Malaga, New Jersey, on a parcel of land which is called "SunCrest", or "the SunCrest Educreational Center".
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] Dinshah served the AVS as its president and as editor of its publication, Ahimsa magazine (1960–2000).
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] In 2000, Dinshah died of a heart attack at age 66, after a life of promoting veganism.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] In 1974, the organization helped to found the North American Vegetarian Society in preparation for hosting the 1975 World Vegetarian Congress in the United States for the first time.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] The American Vegan Society "promotes a compassionate, healthful, and sustainable lifestyle, empowering", and is known for advocating for vegan foods.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] The diet is plant-sourced, varied, and abundant.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] For ethical, health, environmental, and other reasons, (vegans) reject all animal products in food, clothing, and commodities, and the exploitation of animals for sport or entertainment.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] Donald Watson in England (and possibly others) coined the term 'vegan' in 1944; it referred to an entirely plant-based diet (with or without spiritual or philosophical or ethical underpinnings).
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] American Vegan Society used the term vegan to mean dynamic harmlessness and successfully developed a broad social base of practicing vegans who committed themselves to that meaning and practice.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] In 1948, Nimmo and Rubin Abramowitz formed the first vegan organization in the United States known as the U.S.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] The Society lasted from 1948 to 1960 and was a predecessor to the American Vegan Society.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] They both joined this latter one when Dinshah founded it in 1960.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] The American Vegan Society opened the American Vegan Center on September 9, 2021, at 17 North Second Street in Philadelphia's Old City.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] The center has a bookstore, an event space, a demonstration kitchen, and a gift shop.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] It is the first public space operated by the American Vegan Society.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] Journalist Vance Lehmkuhl directs the center and provides 75-minute walking history tours of Philadelphia's vegan history, with stops to discuss Benjamin Lay, Benjamin Franklin, Caroline Earle White, Anthony Benezet, and others, including national figures such as Sylvester Graham.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] Dynamic Harmlessness Day is celebrated on November 2 each year.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] The day remembers American Vegan Society founder Jay Dinshah, who created the term "dynamic harmlessness".
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] Annual Conferences have been held since 1960.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] For a number of years, beginning in 1989, convention proceedings have been videotaped.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] The Dinshahs conducted weekend workshops, cooking classes, and other educational programs at SunCrest in Malaga as early as 1969, when their first building (headquarters) was donated.
[src:american-vegan-society/american-vegan-society] In 1995, the AVS cohosted the 8th International Vegan Festival in San Diego, California, with VUNA (Vegetarian Union of North America) and Vegans International (VI).
